english:
  title: Preface to the Poetry of Snow Valley
  author: Lee Je-hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Snow Valley—Jeong Jung-bu was the son-in-law of Choi Chun-heon and studied under Choi Jeol-ong. Jeol-ong was of lofty temperament and rarely gave his approval to anyone, while Chun-heon was of dignified bearing and showed no favoritism even to those close to him. Yet whenever we met, he would speak to me of Jung-bu's virtue. Thus I came to understand the measure of that man.

    Once Jung-bu entered official service, he rose through the ranks in less than a decade, receiving appointment as Remonstrance Counselor and serving as magistrate of Ul Province, where his governance brought the people great relief. When he departed, the people came forth—the elderly supported by younger hands, children led by their parents—clinging to his carriage with tears streaming down their faces, and none could hold back their weeping.

    Later, bearing the state's memorial to the capital, he was held in high regard by the Chancellor, who wished to recommend him to the throne itself. But illness claimed him before that honor could come to pass. His son Chu bore the coffin back to our eastern lands, and all who heard the news could not help but sigh with wonder and sorrow.

    Alas, history remembers talented men cut short by fate—Li Chang-ji of Tang, Xing Dun of Song—men beloved by the common folk and esteemed by the great. Was Jung-bu not their equal? How fitting, then, that the scholars of the east should marvel and grieve at such untimely loss.

    Chu gathered his father's poems and writings into two volumes, front and back. Reading them through with heavy heart, I have set down these humble words as preface and return them to the Jeong family. Chu now serves as Director of the Ministry of Officials and is, moreover, one of my own students.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Snow Valley (雪谷) appears to be a sobriquet or pen name for Jeong Jung-bu.
  - key: ''
    value: Li Chang-ji (李長吉) was a celebrated Tang poet of great talent who died young, known for his melancholic verse.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Xing Dun (邢敦) and his brother similarly invokes the archetype of gifted men whose lives were cut short despite their promise.
  - key: ''
    value: The author, Lee Je-hyeon (1287-1367), was one of the most prominent scholars and officials of his era in Goryeo Korea.
